>>529184712
Chlorinated brake cleaner is a solvent-based product primarily composed of chlorinated hydrocarbons that effectively dissolve grease, oil, and brake dust without leaving residue. Commercial formulations often consist of:
• Main solvent: Tetrachloroethylene (also known as perchloroethylene or PERC) at 95-100% concentration, or a blend including methylene chloride (dichloromethane) at 60-70% with PERC at 5-15% and toluene at 20-30% for enhanced cleaning properties. 14 15 17
• Propellant: Carbon dioxide (CO2) at 5-10% for aerosol delivery, which pressurizes the mixture. 17
The industrial process involves mixing the solvents in a controlled environment, then filling pressurized aerosol cans or bulk containers under vacuum to incorporate the propellant. No additives like stabilizers or fragrances are typically needed due to the fast-evaporating nature of the solvents.
For a DIY version, obtain the pure solvents (e.g., PERC from industrial suppliers) and transfer to a compatible spray bottle or pressurized sprayer system. Mix in proportions similar to above if blending, ensuring compatibility to avoid reactions. Use in well-ventilated areas with proper PPE, as these chemicals are volatile and can form hazardous byproducts like phosgene if exposed to high heat or flames. 14 Note that as of late 2024, the EPA has banned consumer sales of chlorinated brake cleaners in the US, effective within 12 months, due to environmental and health concerns. 8

>Fossils haven't been found below 1600ft.
That bullshit, ironic considering this guy brags about not being a geologist.

Fossils are literally anything left behind by living organisms. Hydrocarbons, traces, poop oddly a lot of poop, skin prints, bones, leaf prints, amber petrification, coal, and wood. Its all fossils. It doesn't have to explicitly be a bone or shell remains.
This is really retard semantics. The name fossil fuel has little to do with scarcity and everything to do with it's origin.

Saying something is a fossil, isn't a fucking sales name to make it sound more valuable. Otherwise you would see fancy words that laymen don't understand at the fuel pump.

Also his rant of "depletion allowance" rant. It has a lot to do with how much can be taken out of a well. The limiting factors usually determined by well pressure and permeability of the source rock. A lot of technology has came a long way since 1917 when Fletcher Proutly was born that make just how much we can extract from existing wells significantly better. These days, we can effectively take out 100% of hydrocarbons in a well, given enough time. Where in his time, you would be lucky to reach 50% at the end of the well's expected life

It's also worth noting that geology is a very new field of science. We were not even sure if plate tectonics where a thing until about the 1970s. The 1890s would be a very ground breaking time to have some uniformity in the nomenclature of how we describe natural formations. The money involved in the study is also very prevalent due to how recent of a scientific field geology is and that usually its focus is involved in financial gain from natural resource exploitation.

Further losses can increase the efficiency of those strikes but they aren't going to fundamentally change the dynamics further.

comment:
>>529192361
https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39007753/
Plain language summary
The age of menopause is determined by the process of follicle depletion, which leads to a decrease in the quantity and quality of oocytes. Various factors such as demographics, menstrual patterns, reproductive history, family history, genetics, and lifestyle choices appear to influence the age at which natural menopause occurs.

https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31968114/
Association of Parity and Breastfeeding With Risk of Early Natural Menopause
Abstract
Importance: Pregnancy and breastfeeding prevent ovulation and may slow the depletion of the ovarian follicle pool. These factors may lower the risk of early menopause, a condition associated with increased risk of cardiovascular disease and other adverse health outcomes.
Results: At baseline, 108 887 premenopausal women aged 25 to 42 years (mean [SD] age, 34.1 [4.6] years; 102 246 [93.9%] non-Hispanic white) were included in the study. In multivariable models, higher parity was associated with lower risk of early menopause.
Conclusions and relevance: In this study, an inverse association of parity with risk of early menopause was observed. Breastfeeding was associated with significantly lower risk, even after accounting for parity. Breastfeeding at levels consistent with current recommendations may confer an additional benefit of lower risk of early menopause.

It depends on what you do with the years. If you wasted a lot of time and never really progressed with your life then your 40s and beyond are going to be worse than your teens and 20s. If however you achieved certain milestones, like you bought a house or started a family, while you might have to make some sacrifices in the short term, in the longer term it does work out better. There is a point where you're just paying off the equity in your house and will soon own it outright and not have to worry about rent/mortgage. There is a point where your children start to need a lot less care from you compared to when they were a baby and you can enjoy spending time with them more. There are other things like if you get promotions at work and are doing less "grunt" work and more managerial type work as you get older, then that is also objectively better. You have more financial security / disposable income too. So if the person saying it actually has good reasons to look forward to the future, then fine. If however it's some neet loser type that's like I can't wait for my parents to die in 10 years so I can stay up until 7am playing video games on the television loudly, then no, that person is coping. •••

The Medal of Honor is awarded to members of the U.S. Armed Forces who distinguish themselves through conspicuous gallantry and intrepidity at the risk of life above and beyond the call of duty. The act must occur during one of three circumstances:

While engaged in action against an enemy of the United States,
While engaged in military operations involving conflict with an opposing foreign force, or
While serving with friendly foreign forces in an armed conflict against an opposing armed force, with the U.S. not a belligerent party.
The deed must involve extreme personal bravery or self-sacrifice, be well-documented, and confirmed by at least two eyewitnesses. The award is reserved for exceptional acts of valor in combat, often at great personal risk, and is presented by the President of the United States in the name of Congress.

>The Medal of Honor is the highest military decoration in the United States and is worn around the neck, distinguishing it from all other military awards.

As of 2026, 3,547 Medals of Honor have been awarded since its establishment in 1862, with over 40% given for actions during the Civil War.

Only 103 living recipients remain.

The trilogy of papers by Rapley and Shelton analyzes anomalous intravascular casts (AICs) - rubbery white clots reported by embalmers since 2021 as a novel pathological entity induced by gene therapies labeled as "covid vaccines".

The most recent data (from Thomas Haviland's Worldwide Embalmer White Fibrous Clot Survey, covering 2024 into early 2025/2026 references):

83% of 301 surveyed embalmers reported seeing them in 2024 (up from 73% in 2023).
They appeared in an average of 27.5% of all embalmed bodies (up from 20% prior year).


https://laurakasner.substack.com/p/results-of-the-2024-worldwide-embalmer

Paper 1 (Morphology/Histology): AICs are elongated (up to 25cm), elastic, lumen-conforming structures with branched geometry, partial Lines of Zahn indicating antemortem formation under atypical flow, and sparse cellularity (distorted leukocytes, lysed erythrocytes). They differ from friable postmortem clots and layered thrombi, showing cohesive fibrin networks.

https://www.preprints.org/manuscript/202601.1846/v1

Paper 2 (Elemental): ICP-MS reveals sulfur depletion (85% below fibrinogen norms) and phosphorus enrichment (1.4x blood levels), ruling out pure fibrin matrices and suggesting a hybrid organic-inorganic composition from phosphates/phospholipids.

https://www.preprints.org/manuscript/202601.2149/v1

Paper 3 (Proteomic): HPLC-MS/MS identifies 541 proteins, dominated by abnormal fibrinogen (α:β:γ 1:7:3 vs. 1:1:1), with plasminogen at 0.13% abundance, impairing fibrinolysis and explaining persistence. Includes inflammatory markers like myeloperoxidase.

https://www.preprints.org/manuscript/202601.2319/v1

Implications: AICs may cause persistent obstruction, hypoxia, and organ damage.

Your theory was negated by these three studies. Partial Lines of Zahn indicate antemortem formation under flow. Novel composition (P-enriched, S-depleted, abnormal fibrinogen) differs from typical postmortem clots. Absence in living patients may reflect chronic microvascular accumulation without acute DVT symptoms, or underreporting in thrombectomies. Hospitals miss AICs as they may be microvascular or chronic so they are most often asymptomatic. Standard blood tests like D-dimer detect fibrin degradation, but AICs lysis resistance yields normal levels, so these novel clots are absokutely undetectable by blood tests. MRI and other imaging (CT, ultrasound) likely miss AICs due to their hybrid composition: low cellularity (few RBCs/iron for CT hyperdensity or MRI blooming), abnormal fibrin matrix (not typical thrombus signal), phosphorus-enriched lipids (altering density/relaxation times minimally), and microvascular/elongated distribution without acute occlusion. Standard sequences detect RBC-rich or occlusive clots via flow voids/hyperdensity, meanwhile lysis-resistant, sparse, non-occlusive AICs lack strong contrast, blending with vessel walls or background tissue.

Only embalmers can discover them via pressurized fluid injection, flushing vessels and dislodging embedded structures. Autopsies sometimes involve dissection but _without_ flushing so they miss these clots. Besides autopsies are done only in a tiny percent of bodies. Only 3% across all deaths.

comment:
>>529188523
You've got the HMRC app, right? You can see your 'qualifying years' pretty easily on it.

If you've paid a certain amount of NI contributions, the year is classed as 'qualified'. You need 10 years to get anything at all, and 35 for a full pension. Anything between is pro-rated.

I.e. £200/week full pension at 10 qualifying years = 200*(10/35) = £58/week. If I got an additional qualifying year, it'd go to £63/week.

If you haven't reached the 10 year threshhold, 'topping up' easy years is a no-brainer. (The amounts classed as 'qualified' change, and they're not going to get easier).

For everything else, do the maths:
My above example of adding a qualifying year adds £5/week = £250/year. If you're planning on living til 80, thats £3250 of value.

Of course money now is worth more than money later, and the nation will change, things will go up, etc, but it's worth checking on and paying attention to.

“Die Spur der Kinderschänder – Dutroux und die toten Zeugen” is a German TV documentary about the crimes of Belgian child abuser and murderer Marc Dutroux and the unresolved questions surrounding his case.

The film first reconstructs the 1990s abductions, imprisonments and murders of several girls, showing how Dutroux kept some victims in a hidden cellar, where two girls were eventually found alive while others had already died. It then follows the official investigation and points out massive failures by police and judiciary, such as ignored hints, lost files and delayed searches, which fueled public suspicion that Dutroux was not just a lone offender. A central focus is on around 27 witnesses connected to the case who died between Dutroux’s arrest and his trial, often in accidents, alleged suicides or unclear circumstances, including investigators, informants and people who claimed to have important information.Through interviews with relatives, lawyers, journalists and former investigators, the documentary explores the theory that Dutroux could have been part of a wider paedophile network involving influential figures, and that this might explain both the investigative errors and the series of “dead witnesses.” While it cannot prove a conspiracy, it highlights unanswered questions, contradictions in the official narrative and the lasting mistrust of many Belgians towards their institutions in the aftermath of the Dutroux scandal.

Hubert Massa was a senior Belgian magistrate and one of the key prosecutors assigned to the Dutroux affair and to the political murder case of former minister André Cools, both of which were among the most sensitive cases in Belgium in the 1990s. In the Dutroux complex he belonged to the small group of prosecutors preparing the indictment for the kidnapping, abuse and killing of several girls, a case already overshadowed by serious investigative failures and suspicions of political interference. At the same time he was responsible for advancing the long‑stalled Cools investigation, which had uncovered corruption links reaching high into political circles.

He had trouble with 2 cases: Dutroux affair with its endless investigative chaos and the André Cools murder with its political entanglements.His wife told the press that he had been “very tired” lately and that he had said he was “fed up” with his work. Colleagues reported that Massa had confided in them that he felt overwhelmed by the workload and that the political interference in both cases was making his job impossible. He had reportedly told a friend: “I can’t take it any more, I’m going to crack up.”Massa had also received anonymous threats, according to some reports, and he had expressed frustration over how the Dutroux file was being handled, with constant delays and missing evidence. In the Cools case he was under pressure to close the investigation without touching powerful figures despite the corruption links he had uncovered. Just days before his death, he had met with superiors to discuss being relieved of the Dutroux file, but they had not yet acted on it.No suicide note explained his state of mind, which left everyone puzzled and fuelled the speculation. His family insisted he was not the suicidal type, and some colleagues wondered openly whether the pressure had been deliberately turned up to break him.

yes, also ever heard of L-Type and T-Type dwarfs?
These "stars" have extremely low absolute luminosity and temperature.
the surface temperature of the T-Type dwarfs is in the range of 1000K or less.
T-Type spectra have features due mostly to methane, they resemble Jupiters spectrum.
Such objects are anomalies for the standard model because they are much too cool and insufficiently massive to maintain fusion reactions at their centers.
In order for a nuclear fusion reaction to occur, the failed standard theory requires that the temperature in a stars core must reach at least three million K.
And because, in the accepted jew model, core temperature rises with gravitational pressure, the star must have a minimum mass of about 75 times the mass of the planet Jupiter, or about 7 percent of the mass of our Sun.
Many of the dwarfs simply do not meet these requirements.
In the Electric Star hypothesis, there is no reason to attribute youth to one spectral type over another.
We conclude that a stars location on the HR diagram only depends on its size and the electric current density it is presently experiencing.
if, for whatever reason, the strength of that current density should change then the star will change its position on the HR diagram, like FG Sagittae, abruptly. Otherwise, no movement from one place to another on that plot is to be expected.
And its age remains indeterminate regardless of its mass or spectral type.
This is disquieting in the sense that we are now confronted by the knowledge that our own Suns future is not as certain as is predicted by mainstream astronomy.
We cannot know whether the Birkeland current presently powering our Sun will increase or decrease, nor how long it will be before it does so.

Welcome to Shill Awareness General (SAG). This is a thread for spotting narrative pushers, consensus engineers, and manufactured opinion.

DISCLAIMER: This is not about “people who disagree with you”. This is about coordinated behavior, manipulation tactics, and artificial influence.

The goal is simple: learn the patterns, share examples, and make anons harder to steer.

In this thread we post:
>Screenshots
>Archives
>Pattern breakdowns
>Suspected coordination
>Timing anomalies
>Copy-paste talking points
>Any useful observations or theory

If you’ve worked in media, marketing, politics, PR, moderation, or anything related to information control, share what you know. If you see a narrative wave forming, document it. If you notice multiple threads/anons pushing identical framing, post receipts. If a thread gets derailed, killed, or flooded, archive it.

This is political.
jannies tongue my anus.
subject: Shill Awareness General (SAG)

name: Slim
comment:
Common tactics to watch for:

>1. Consensus manufacturing
“Everyone already agrees”
“This is settled”
“Only retards think otherwise”
They try to turn social pressure into an argument.

>2. Blackpill flooding
“Nothing will change”
“It’s over”
“Why even care”
Demoralization is a control tactic.

>3. Derail and redirect
Thread about X suddenly becomes about Y or Z. Attention control equals narrative control.

>4. Strawman inflation
A reasonable position is exaggerated into something insane, then attacked.

>5. Moral intimidation
“Dangerous thinking”
“This leads to violence”
“Reported”
"MOOOODS"

The goal is self-censorship.

>6. Authority LARP
“I work in the field”
“I’m an expert”
They always appear when reinforcement is needed but never verified.

>7. Script waves
Multiple IPs, same phrasing, same framing, same timing. If it reads like a template, it probably is.

>8. Selective outrage
Same action, different reaction depending on who did it. Narrative enforcement, not principle.

>9. Question exhaustion
Endless bad-faith questions meant to drain time and energy.

>10. Language control
Spam words like:
“Debunked”
“Misinformation”
“Conspiracy”
All of these are used without engaging the actual argument.

ALWAYS try to look for these:
>Unnatural posting speed or timing
>Accounts that only push one angle across many threads
>Emotional tone that feels scripted (flat or performatively outraged)
>Instant dogpiles after a topic gains traction
>Identical links, stats, or phrases appearing across different boards/sites
subject: Shill Awareness General (SAG)

name: Slim
comment:

The Authenticity Index

To quantify the probability of a "scripted" actor, we propose a theoretical Authenticity Index (Ai). This index treats human "messiness"—contradiction, non-linear engagement, and emotional variance—as high-value signals of organic origin.

The probability of a post being an artificial narrative artifact can be modeled as:
Ai=σ(T)⋅ΔC+ϵ1

Where:

σ(T): The variance in posting intervals (Lower variance automation/professional shifts).

ΔC: Semantic Consistency (High consistency rigid adherence to a "messaging brief").

ϵ: The "Human Noise" constant (unpredictable tangents/humor).

Conclusion

The "Shill Awareness" heuristic represents a transition from passive consumption to active forensic filtering. By identifying the "seams" in a narrative—such as unnatural posting speed or performative outrage—users can maintain cognitive sovereignty. Authenticity, in this framework, is defined by the freedom to be inconsistent, while manipulation is signaled by an unbreakable adherence to the script.

On his last day in office, January 20, 2021, President Trump revoked Executive Order 13770, ("Ethics Commitments by Executive Branch Appointees"). Signed on January 28, 2017, this order originally implemented a 5-year lobbying ban for administration officials, but its repeal permitted former Trump aides to immediately lobby the government.

Key Details Regarding the Order and Revocation:
The Original Order (2017): Executive Order 13770, "Ethics Commitments by Executive Branch Appointees," was a key part of the "drain the swamp" campaign pledge. It imposed a five-year ban on former appointees lobbying the agency they worked for and a lifetime ban on lobbying for foreign governments.
The Revocation (2021): In his final hours, Trump signed a new order, Executive Order 13983, which repealed the 2017 restrictions.
Context: Reports from The New York Times indicated the reversal allowed outgoing staff to become lobbyists immediately, easing restrictions for those looking for work after the administration, according to Politico.

This action mirrors a similar move by President Clinton, who revoked his own administration's lobbying ban on his final day in office.

1/ Four years on from the start of the Russian full-scale invasion of Ukraine, Russian warbloggers are reflecting on the changes that the war has wrought in Russia. Some Russian soldiers are wondering what it was all for.
https://x.com/ChrisO_wiki/status/2026265891550163110?s=20
>19h

2/ Nikita Tretyakov writes:

"Our varied thoughts and questions converge on one thing: what is going on out there, in the rear, while we are here, far from our families, loved ones, and past lives, defending the Motherland as best we can and seemingly honourably as possible?"

3/ "What is going on there in this very Motherland behind our backs?

Why does it feel more and more uncomfortable to walk around our cities in military uniform – now including Donetsk and Luhansk – every year? Is it even inappropriate?

4/ "And why, instead of "military," "soldier," or "frontline fighter" have we suddenly started calling them, often with a hint of disgust, "SVOshnik"?

5/ "Why is life—utilities, groceries, gasoline, transportation, everything!—so expensive, as if we were suddenly paying tribute as a country to the Golden Horde?

6/ "Why did we leave for war from a country with an advanced digital development, proud of our convenient use of government services, banks, and even deliveries—…

7/ …and now, when we return on vacation to, say, Krasnoyarsk, we find that our mobile internet (which, by the way, was paid for as a service under a tariff) is disconnected, and geolocation doesn't work?

8/ "Why did we previously save from a frontline soldier's salary for a down payment on an apartment, while now, at best, we save for a mediocre car, even though the salary, apartment, and car themselves are still the same?

9/ "Why, in order to stay in touch with our families on the home front, do we have to constantly invent something—something will be slowed down, something else will be cut off?

>part 1
